Have you ever imagined how to call or name someone who has no first or last name?
Hey!
Thou!
That word that identifies us Argentines so much, "che".
But I'm thinking of someone else who doesn't have a first or last name.
I'm thinking of that someone who lost his name and his surname, who disappeared his first and his last name, his identity.
Now in Argentina people are disappearing.
In the world, now at this moment, thousands of people disappear.
Some are disappeared who are alive, product of child trafficking, theft of babies, human trafficking, illegal adoptions.
Others are disappeared who have died: kidnappings, wars, drug violence, terrorist attacks, natural accidents and others not so natural.
It is necessary to return their identity, rewrite their name and surname.
Because we all have an identity, we have an individuality, an identity of individual, affective, family, cultural, group, country, but we also have a genetic identity.
Our identity is written in our genes.
Our genome, the human genome, is made up of four letters that are repeated 3 billion times.
Incredible!
But we are almost the same.
Almost the same!
To be exact, our genome is 99.9% identical to each other.
Only 0.1% of our genome allows us to distinguish or identify ourselves.
Now, 0.1% of 3000 million letters is no less than three million letters and that is a number.
Some books with three million letters can be written.
And that's what it's about, using the letters of our genome, rewriting the letters of the name and surname of those who lost their identity.
How do we do it?
Using genetics, comparing.
To identify necessarily is to compare.
To compare a father and a son, to know if they are linked in that relationship, I have to compare them.
And to know that there is a proportion of those letters that they have in common according to that kinship.
In the 80s, I had been working at the Hospital de Clínicas, in the genetics of transplants, looking for the maximum genetic compatibility between donors and recipients of organs to avoid graft rejection.
And you may ask, what does that have to do with identity?
It has to do and a lot.
And how much!
Because our organism, our immune system, is profoundly xenophobic.
It recognizes itself as such and tolerates and rejects everything strange.
And that's why we reject a virus, a bacterium, how much more are we going to reject an entire organ.
That's why we looked for those compatibilities, to avoid those rejections.
But these genes also allowed us, precisely because we did it between related relatives, to analyze and establish kinship links.
We had a problem in the 80s: we needed living cells from the two people we were going to compare, we couldn't analyze a bone.
That was a stumbling block.
But a decade later a revolution came to laboratories: we could now compare molecules.
We could extract molecules from a living, or dead, cell and compare them.
Then we took a step forward and could then identify a dead cell inside a body or a bone remnant.
And we gained some experience.
A decade later, precisely in 2003, something happened that changed my life, largely professionally and also in motivation.
A group of women and men, anthropologists and anthropologists, from the Argentine Forensic Anthropology Team arrived in Córdoba who had been walking through Argentina, exhuming graves, looking for causes of death, analyzing those bones, trying to identify them and return them to the families.
They were walking not only in Argentina, but in many countries of the world.
And they came to Córdoba to exhume a massive grave from the municipal cemetery of San Vicente.
A mutual friend met us at his house.
What did we do?
What many Argentines do when we get together: we ate a barbecue and there was wine too.
And then, having a few glasses of wine, I was shocked by the stories that these anthropologists told me because the Argentine Forensic Anthropology Team is an NGO that works on cases of violation of universal human rights trying to identify people.
They told me stories from all the countries, but there, in that meeting, in that roast with that wine, we realized that they were in a stumbling block, there was a stalemate, they needed to incorporate a new technology into this complex process of identification and it was genetics.
So, we thought about joining forces and doing something in common.
I remember that at that moment we considered, let's try with the worst preserved rest of the San Vicente pit, with the rest more degraded, more deteriorated.
If we do well with that one, we will surely do well with the others.
And we did very well.
And the first identification of a skeletal remains of the dictatorship in Argentina emerged, in the San Vicente grave in Córdoba.
That filled us with joy and we said: "let's put a laboratory" and so it was done.
We set up a genetics laboratory where there are young guys who are working, I know, a lot.
And we started walking, we summoned relatives, we started crossing letters to rewrite names.
But not only in Argentina, because in Argentina we produced some identifications, others more from the cemetery of San Vicente, from the torture and death center of "La Perla", the identification of some of the founding mothers of Plaza de Mayo, who had been thrown into the sea and that the sea had returned them.
We also went out to walk the path they had been walking: Uruguay, Paraguay, Bolivia, where there were also dictatorships and names and identities disappeared.
And further north, in Central America, El Salvador, the war of the 80s, and even further north, in today's Mexico, where thousands of migrants disappear every year from many countries, who crossing Mexico, want to achieve the dream of the northern country.
Also on other continents, Africa, for example, the South Africa that imprisoned Mandela.
And in Asia.
It all seems wonderful, doesn't it?
Everything went well.
But that's not the case.
Many times we stay in the middle.
Many times we have the remains, but so many years have passed that the relatives are no longer there.
And other times we have the relatives, but the remains are not found.
And other times, even if we have the remains, they are so deteriorated that we cannot decipher the letters to compare them with the relatives.
That generates a lot of frustration really.
I'm sure you know a well-known, very famous, popular TV series: CSI New York, Los Angeles, Miami.
In these series, the investigators, in hours, days, solve some very difficult cases.
That's not true, that's fiction.
The reality is different.
We call this the "CSI effect" because they generate a distorted picture of the complex identification process.
The most worrying thing is that they don't just do it over people popularly, but some government officials also believe it's so easy.
On top of that, they are all models.
Our reality... (Laughter) It's a little different.
(Laughter) (Whistling in the audience) (Laughter) (Applause) I am remembering about four or five years ago, I had to participate in a call that we had made in Mexico to relatives.
It was a call to a number of families who came to donate their blood samples to make a blood bank and compare the data with the number of graves that were discovered.
It was a very solemn atmosphere.
The relatives were serious, they came to donate their blood samples.
At one point, I finished taking a sample from a mother.
He stopped.
I was going to reach out to him to give it to him.
I looked at her, she was tiny, very native, dressed in her typical costume.
I extended my hand to her and she took it with both of us and brought her here and said, "Little doctor, please find it for me."
(Sigh) That request is a mandate.
It is because of this mandate-request that it is worth insisting and insisting on those complex cases that we cannot solve.
Obsessively insisting to try to produce a new identity, to be able to rewrite a name again, to return it to a family, to end the years of waiting, uncertainty, anguish and so that that little mother can meet her son again, even if her son is already dead.
Thanks a lot.
