When I was five years old and starting to read, my dear grandfather Carlos Felipe gave me an adventure book.
"The Microbe Hunters", by Paul de Kruif.
In its chapters were Leeuwenhoek, Spallanzani, Koch, the one with the bacillus, Pasteur, men who with rudimentary microscopes sought to defeat the invisible enemy.
The book did not awaken in me the vocation for medicine or chemistry, but it did awaken my passion for history.
And, as a frequent traveler to the past, I wanted to tell you something about the pandemics that hit humanity.
We could speak of the fierce cholera of the second half of the nineteenth century, or of the smallpox that cost so much to master.
But there are two pandemics that were very marked by their fatal consequences.
In the fourteenth century, the Black Death, provoked by a louse that moved in rats.
He started in Asia and from there went to Venice, the most cosmopolitan port of his time.
That's how he got into Europe.
The mortality was between 25 and 50 million.
Out of every four Europeans, one was struck by the plague.
The numbers in Asia were quite similar.
Closer in time, in the twentieth century, the century of flu, we had in 1918 the Spanish flu.
Spanish flu that began in the U.S. with American soldiers preparing to go to the end of World War I and that infected the populations of the ports of France where they embarked.
From there it spread throughout the continent.
It started in the U.S. and came to Europe through France.
Why do we call it the Spanish flu?
Well, that was fake news.
Spain's government and press decided to confront the evil by bringing statistics to the surface.
Because of this honesty of the data and the numbers, they ended up being pointed out as responsible for something that did not correspond to them.
On that occasion, one in five infected died.
Look, in World War I, between 10 and 30 million people died.
The universal flu killed 50 million.
The world's population was reduced by 2.5% to 5% because of that pandemic.
We talked about cholera, smallpox, the Black Death, the universal flu and we could also add the yellow fever, of 1871, which hit the cities of Corrientes and Buenos Aires.
What did they all have in common?
That when they attacked us we were not warned.
We weren't prepared.
To make matters worse, in many cases it was not known where the contagion came from.
Therefore, responses and reactions were not effective in counteracting evil.
What did we learn from all those fatalities?
Something very important, that the danger of the virus is enhanced by misinformation.
Let me explain.
In the fourteenth century, instead of dealing with rats and poor hygiene, it was held that the sinful lifestyle of many had unleashed divine wrath.
In the twentieth century, instead of showing the true causes of that flu, reality was distorted and the bug was out of control.
In this way it spread over the five continents.
Therefore, we may have learned at once that we must deal with the truth.
As much as it hurts us.
Another of the great lessons on that occasion was that we will have to stay on guard even after the storm passes.
Because there have always been second and third waves that have taken the unsuspecting.
But, above all, we can venture wonderful times of growth.
Because after the Black Death came the Renaissance.
Because after the universal flu came the 1920s, the most fruitful and avant-garde of all time.
Yes, at the end of the tunnel, the sun awaits us.
Thank you.
