You probably remember this image of Chancellor Angela Merkel taking a selfie with a refugee.
This image and others like it raised blisters in the German parliament and in many European parliaments, putting the European Union in check.
From the beginning there was no consensus among the German population in the face of such an avalanche of refugees from the Middle East, on their way to Europe.
The welcoming culture fostered by Angela Merkel from the beginning was not always valued by everyone.
From the beginning there were people who supported her and others who did not.
The people who do not currently support her, there are more and more, there are more and more detractors, and this is going to take its toll on Angela Merkel, obviously.
I do not want to go into detail about Angela Merkel's political future, but I would like to mention that she, for me, is one of the political people today who has a moral authority despite her mistakes, which most current politicians lack.
This is a graph showing the number of refugees who entered Germany over the past year.
The first group is from Syria, followed by the group that came from Iraq, and the group that came from Afghanistan.
According to a UNICEF report released just two weeks ago, half of those fleeing war are children.
The discourse against refugees is well known: "They are going to Islamize us."
"We are letting terrorists in."
"We're losing our identity."
And it is true that there are also people who are very much in favour or empathize with people fleeing war, but I can also see that among these people there is a kind of hiding behind the mistakes of politicians in order not to act, not to participate in initiatives that can, if not solve, at least alleviate these serious personal tragedies.
In the informal discourse and in the official discourse, learning German stands out as key to the integration of refugees.
I'm from Barcelona, I'm a linguist.
I have been living in Cologne, Germany, for four years, and for me language learning is also a key factor to be able to integrate, but not only for refugees it is a key factor, but for all immigrants in general.
I have been researching different aspects of language in multilingual environments for several years, and for me language is not a final product that can be mastered.
For me, language is a process that changes throughout life, throughout the personal experiences we have.
Obviously, language is a powerful instrument of integration, of inclusion, but also a powerful instrument of social exclusion.
If, for example, you have poor language proficiency or have a foreign accent, or a certain dialect from a region, or, perhaps, you have some kind of disability that affects your oral language production, such as stuttering, these are all examples that influence how people will accept you or marginalize you in a society.
The use of language and identity is not something static, it is something that is changing.
It's not like fingerprints, which is what accompanies you all your life.
Identity is something that is created or forged based on the values and beliefs that your family gives you, your friends give you and also goes according to what you really want to be, and what you really want to be is based on your motivation, the feeling of belonging you have with other groups with which you feel related or identified and also depending on the interactions with groups that are totally different from you.
Free German lessons are offered in refugee centres in Germany, and one might think, it is natural to think, that these people should be happy to be able to receive these German courses and also that they should be grateful.
But the absence of adolescent girls in these German groups, in these activities, is really significant.
Put yourselves in a situation: these girls carry a lot of burden, many post-traumatic disorders, due to an exodus, to a land that nobody had promised them, they have seen how their loved ones were murdered, they have seen how their houses were burned or bombed, others unfortunately have also witnessed or victims of rape in their particular transfer from Afghanistan, Iraq and Syria on their way to Europe,  or road in this case of Germany.
If you put yourself in their shoes, would you feel like taking German classes or anything else?
To make matters worse, the families of these girls, parents, siblings or other relatives, prevent them from participating in these activities because they think that, perhaps, they will harm them even more.
And the question is: What can be done so that these girls begin to participate in this new society and that they can integrate?
This is the question we made four friends: with the red sweater, Sandra, then there is me, Lina and Peter.
All four of us, for different reasons, have a lot to do with adolescence.
Peter and I, for having fifteen-year-old daughters.
And Sandra and Lina, for also working with this group, adolescence.
We thought: what if we do a project where it is not only attractive to refugee girls, but also attractive to German girls?
Could we manage to unite them?
Could we create a space for them to interact and perhaps contribute to transforming their identity?
Thus was born the initiative of HalloFoto!.
It is an intercultural project for adolescent girls between 13 and 17 years old.
The objectives of this project were: to develop... Well, first create these spaces of interaction to be able to develop communicative skills.
And the creative skills of the girls.
We thought: if we develop both, we will surely create the possibility for them to develop intercultural competences as well.
Obviously, to develop communicative skills you had to go through learning German, there was no other, and we used a novel method: augmentative communication boards.
Augmentative communication boards are aids for people who are nonverbal, that is, people who do not have oral language.
This condition can occur from birth, for example in the case of children with severe autism spectrum disorders, or for example in children with cerebral palsy.
This condition can also occur when you are an adult, because you have a stroke or because you have an accident, or because you suffer from a neurodegenerative disease, such as Parkinson's.
These boards that we use for the project are composed of pictograms and core vocabulary.
The core vocabulary is the words that are repeated most in the spontaneous language and this happens, not only in German, but also in Spanish, Catalan, Basque, English, etc.
The truth is that the girls accepted these instruments very well, and the data collected in the project show that yes, they value it positively.
In any case, for them this is not what is decisive to learn German, to have dreams, to be motivated, to really want to participate in this new society.
For them, what is really significant are the meetings that we form, that we organize in HalloFoto!, in our project.
They are intercultural encounters because we were encouraging face-to-face interaction of groups with totally different frames of reference.
This, for example, is the image of one of the encounters.
We organize these intercultural meetings by theme and the themes were decided by them.
This is the theme "Makeup and hairdressing".
In another of the meetings we went to an adventure center where there were zip lines, there were balance games, tunnels.
The issue was not to create fear, but to overcome fear.
Together they were helping each other, and it was not a question of who was more afraid or less afraid, which group was the most afraid or less, it was simply each in its own expression.
You see it in their faces, they can't define who's who, the one who is afraid.
The fact is that in this, along with other encounters... —This is the meeting we did about cooking.— they see meaning.
And it is in this construction of meaning that generates a sense of miscegenation, a feeling of creating links, intercultural developments that go beyond labels.
The labels only generate stereotypes and generate prejudices that do not account for the great wealth that each one of us is, or that each one of us has.
In addition to communicative skills, we also wanted to develop creative skills.
Creativity is the affective and cognitive expression of each individual.
And if we activate that expression together, first, a space is developed to generate things, first unthinkable, which are miscegenations of expressions where we can already begin to see how an intercultural competence is being forged.
That's why these photography workshops were held, to generate this creativity.
The photography workshops were done by Peter and Sandra, who are the photographers of the group.
And these are the photos that the girls took throughout the project.
Sometimes they posed and sometimes they were photographers, they decided.
And when you see these photos you think: where is the "they"?
Where is the "we"?
The borders are very diluted.
How do we define ourselves?
We found the photos so beautiful that we thought we should do an exhibition.
But we didn't want to do an exhibition to use, we didn't want to do an exhibition in a museum or in an art gallery.
We wanted to move our photos, our exhibition, to an urban space and we had a vision.
This is the computer recreation of our vision: we wanted our girls to be on a tram, the tram of desire.
Our desire was to have a platform, a platform that would be a political statement against sexism and against xenophobia.
We presented it to public transport in Cologne and they were quite enthusiastic about the project.
And at the beginning of July, last July, the tram with the photos of the girls was presented.
(Applause) The project was much more successful than we imagined.
In fact, the press highlighted us as an exemplary project, to counteract the xenophobic tendencies that are sadly increasing, not only in Germany, but throughout Europe.
Likewise, there were many people who asked us if they could replicate the project, if they could make their special HalloFoto!.
And for this reason we think: we are going to license it, so that everyone can use it.
That is why the project is in Creative Commons, and from this scenario, from TEDxValladolid, I invite all those who want to participate and launch their own project, to do so.
(Applause) And it's not what we have taught, the four people on the team, but what the girls have taught us.
All the participants in the group have shown us ways to communicate and ways to interact.
First, they break stereotypes.
Second, they create bridges.
That they have also generated transformed, powerful and intercultural identities, and these intercultural identities are not based on consensus, but on mutual respect, on that mutual respect of empathizing with the other, of putting themselves in the shoes of the other, in order to have that feeling of belonging.
And that sense of belonging is what I've been feeling before you as I was telling you all this, and for this I'm very grateful to you.
